      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(googlechat): expose sender bot status in context",
        "body": "**Prompt request:** Make the Google Chat channel forward sender bot status into the inbound agent context so an operator running `allowBots` can tell a bot sender from a human, matching what Telegram already exposes, while preserving existing bot detection and filtering.\n\n## What Problem This Solves\n\nGoogle Chat already detects whether an inbound message was sent by a bot (`sender.type === \"BOT\"`) and uses that for loop protection, but it never forwards the fact to the agent. With `allowBots: true`, a bot-sent message reaches the agent indistinguishable from a human one: the \"Sender (untrusted metadata)\" block in the prompt has no `is_bot` field. Operators wiring bot-to-bot or integration flows on Google Chat therefore cannot have the agent treat bot senders differently, even though Telegram exposes this today.\n\n## Why This Change Was Made\n\nThe shared inbound context already carries sender bot status end-to-end: `buildChannelInboundEventContext` maps `sender.isBot` to `SenderIsBot`, which renders as `is_bot` in the untrusted sender metadata block. Telegram populates it; Google Chat computes the same signal (`isBotSender`) but does not pass it through. This change forwards that existing flag into the `sender` object Google Chat already builds, so no core or SDK change is needed. This PR only changes the Google Chat adapter's inbound context assembly and its tests.\n\n## User Impact\n\nOperators with `allowBots` enabled now see `\"is_bot\": true` in the untrusted sender metadata for bot-sent Google Chat messages, letting their agent or system prompt branch on sender type (for example, not auto-replying to other bots). Human messages are unaffected — the field is simply absent. There is no change when `allowBots` is off, where bot messages are still filtered as before.\n\n## Evidence\n\nDirect production-path run via `node --import tsx` — real production functions with no mocked I/O, not a vitest or CI run (Google Chat's inbound access policy needs live pairing/credential infra that is not reproducible offline, so the production core context builder `buildChannelInboundEventContext` and the prompt renderer `buildInboundUserContextPrefix` were invoked directly, using the exact sender expressions the Google Chat monitor builds: `isBotSender = sender.type === \"BOT\"`, then the `sender` object with `isBot: isBotSender || undefined`), for a bot sender and a human sender. Redacted terminal output of the agent-visible `Sender (untrusted metadata)` block:\n\n~~~text\n=== bot sender (sender.type === BOT) ===\nsender.isBot (monitor build) = true  ->  ctxPayload.SenderIsBot = true\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n{\n  \"label\": \"Deploy Bot (redacted-bot-id)\",\n  \"id\": \"redacted-bot-id\",\n  \"name\": \"Deploy Bot\",\n  \"is_bot\": true\n}\n\n=== human sender ===\nsender.isBot (monitor build) = undefined  ->  ctxPayload.SenderIsBot = undefined\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n{\n  \"label\": \"Alice (redacted-user-id)\",\n  \"id\": \"redacted-user-id\",\n  \"name\": \"Alice\",\n  \"username\": \"alice@example.com\"\n}\n~~~\n\nA bot sender reaches the agent prompt with `is_bot: true` in the untrusted sender metadata; a human sender omits the field. The same bot and human behavior is also asserted by focused unit tests in `monitor.test.ts`.\n",
        "branch": "fix/googlechat-sender-bot-status",
